#: ../../../spack.rst:295
msgid "spack.multimethod module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod:1
msgid ""
"This module contains utilities for using multi-methods in spack. You can "
"think of multi-methods like overloaded methods -- they're methods with the "
"same name, and we need to select a version of the method based on some "
"criteria.  e.g., for overloaded methods, you would select a version of the "
"method to call based on the types of its arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod:8
msgid ""
"In spack, multi-methods are used to ease the life of package authors.  They "
"allow methods like install() (or other methods called by install()) to "
"declare multiple versions to be called when the package is instantiated with "
"different specs.  e.g., if the package is built with OpenMPI on x86_64,, you "
"might want to call a different install method than if it was built for "
"mpich2 on BlueGene/Q.  Likewise, you might want to do a different type of "
"install for different versions of the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod:17
msgid ""
"Multi-methods provide a simple decorator-based syntax for this that avoids "
"overly complicated rat nests of if statements.  Obviously, depending on the "
"scenario, regular old conditionals might be clearer, so package authors "
"should use their judgement."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.MultiMethodError:1
msgid "Superclass for multimethod dispatch errors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.MultiMethodMeta:1
msgid "This allows us to track the class's dict during instantiation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.NoSuchMethodError:1
msgid "Raised when we can't find a version of a multi-method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.SpecMultiMethod:1
msgid ""
"This implements a multi-method for Spack specs.  Packages are instantiated "
"with a particular spec, and you may want to execute different versions of "
"methods based on what the spec looks like.  For example, you might want to "
"call a different version of install() for one platform than you call on "
"another."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.SpecMultiMethod:7
msgid ""
"The SpecMultiMethod class implements a callable object that handles method "
"dispatch.  When it is called, it looks through registered methods and their "
"associated specs, and it tries to find one that matches the package's spec.  "
"If it finds one (and only one), it will call that method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.SpecMultiMethod:13
msgid ""
"This is intended for use with decorators (see below).  The decorator (see "
"docs below) creates SpecMultiMethods and registers method versions with them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.SpecMultiMethod:17
msgid "To register a method, you can do something like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.SpecMultiMethod:19
msgid ""
"mm = SpecMultiMethod()\n"
"mm.register(\"^chaos_5_x86_64_ib\", some_method)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.SpecMultiMethod:22
msgid ""
"The object registered needs to be a Spec or some string that will parse to "
"be a valid spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.SpecMultiMethod:25
msgid ""
"When the ``mm`` is actually called, it selects a version of the method to "
"call based on the ``sys_type`` of the object it is called on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.SpecMultiMethod:29
msgid "See the docs for decorators below for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.SpecMultiMethod.register:1
msgid "Register a version of a method for a particular spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.default_args:1
msgid "Context manager to override the default arguments of directives."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.default_args:5
msgid ""
"with default_args(type=(\"build\", \"run\")):\n"
"    depends_on(\"py-foo\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"py-bar\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"py-baz\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.default_args:10
msgid ""
"Notice that unlike then :func:`when` context manager, this one is *not* "
"composable, as it merely overrides the default argument values for the "
"duration of the context. For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.default_args:13
msgid ""
"with default_args(when=\"+foo\"):\n"
"    depends_on(\"pkg-a\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"pkg-b\", when=\"+bar\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.default_args:17
msgid "is equivalent to::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.default_args:19
msgid ""
"depends_on(\"pkg-a\", when=\"+foo\")\n"
"depends_on(\"pkg-b\", when=\"+bar\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:1
msgid "This is a multi-purpose class, which can be used"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:3
msgid ""
"As a context manager to **group directives together** that share the same "
"``when=`` argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:5
msgid ""
"As a **decorator** for defining multi-methods (multiple methods with the "
"same name are defined, but the version that is called depends on the "
"condition of the package's spec)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:8
msgid ""
"As a **context manager** it groups directives together. It allows you to "
"write::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:10
msgid ""
"with when(\"+nvptx\"):\n"
"    conflicts(\"@:6\", msg=\"NVPTX only supported from gcc 7\")\n"
"    conflicts(\"languages=ada\")\n"
"    conflicts(\"languages=brig\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:15
msgid "instead of the more repetitive::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:17
msgid ""
"conflicts(\"@:6\", when=\"+nvptx\", msg=\"NVPTX only supported from gcc "
"7\")\n"
"conflicts(\"languages=ada\", when=\"+nvptx\")\n"
"conflicts(\"languages=brig\", when=\"+nvptx\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:21
msgid ""
"This context manager is composable both with nested ``when`` contexts and "
"with other ``when=`` arguments in directives. For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:24
msgid ""
"with when(\"+foo\"):\n"
"    with when(\"+bar\"):\n"
"        depends_on(\"dependency\", when=\"+baz\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:28
msgid "is equilavent to::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:30
msgid "depends_on(\"dependency\", when=\"+foo +bar +baz\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:32
msgid ""
"As a **decorator**, it allows packages to declare multiple versions of "
"methods like ``install()`` that depend on the package's spec. For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:35
msgid ""
"class SomePackage(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    def install(self, spec: Spec, prefix: Prefix):\n"
"        # Do default install\n"
"\n"
"    @when(\"target=x86_64:\")\n"
"    def install(self, spec: Spec, prefix: Prefix):\n"
"        # This will be executed instead of the default install if\n"
"        # the package's target is in the x86_64 family.\n"
"\n"
"    @when(\"target=aarch64:\")\n"
"    def install(self, spec: Spec, prefix: Prefix):\n"
"        # This will be executed if the package's target is in\n"
"        # the aarch64 family"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:51
msgid ""
"This allows each package to have a default version of ``install()`` AND "
"specialized versions for particular platforms.  The version that is called "
"depends on the architecture of the instantiated package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:55
msgid ""
"Note that this works for methods other than install, as well.  So, if you "
"only have part of the install that is platform specific, you could do this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:59
msgid ""
"class SomePackage(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    # virtual dependence on MPI.\n"
"    # could resolve to mpich, mpich2, OpenMPI\n"
"    depends_on(\"mpi\")\n"
"\n"
"    def setup(self):\n"
"        # do nothing in the default case\n"
"        pass\n"
"\n"
"    @when(\"^openmpi\")\n"
"    def setup(self):\n"
"        # do something special when this is built with OpenMPI for its MPI "
"implementations.\n"
"        pass\n"
"\n"
"    def install(self, prefix):\n"
"        # Do common install stuff\n"
"        self.setup()\n"
"        # Do more common install stuff"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/multimethod.py:docstring of
#: spack.multimethod.when:81
msgid ""
"Note that the default version of decorated methods must *always* come first. "
"Otherwise it will override all of the decorated versions. This is a "
"limitation of the Python language."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../spack.rst:303
msgid "spack.new\\_installer module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/new_installer.py:docstring of
#: spack.new_installer:1
msgid ""
"New installer that will ultimately replace installer.py. It features an "
"event loop, non-blocking I/O, and a POSIX jobserver to limit concurrency. It "
"also has a more advanced terminal UI. It's mostly self-contained to avoid "
"interfering with the rest of Spack too much while it's being developed and "
"tested."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/new_installer.py:docstring of
#: spack.new_installer:6
msgid ""
"The installer consists of a UI process that manages multiple build processes "
"and handles updates to the database. It detects or creates a jobserver, and "
"then kicks off an event loop in which it runs through a build queue, always "
"running at least one build. Concurrent builds run as jobserver tokens are "
"obtained. This means only one -j flag is needed to control concurrency."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/new_installer.py:docstring of
#: spack.new_installer:11
msgid ""
"The UI process has two modes: an overview mode where it shows the status of "
"all builds, and a mode where it follows the logs of a specific build. It "
"listens to keyboard input to switch between modes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/new_installer.py:docstring of
#: spack.new_installer:15
msgid ""
"The build process does an ordinary install, but also spawns a \"tee\" thread "
"that forwards its build output to both a log file and the UI process (if the "
"UI process has requested it). This thread also runs an event loop to listen "
"for control messages from the UI process (to enable/disable echoing of "
"logs), and for output from the build process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/new_installer.py:docstring of
#: spack.new_installer.BuildGraph:1
msgid "Represents the dependency graph for package installation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../_spack_root/lib/spack/spack/new_installer.py:docstring of
